Pulling numbers that range from 0 to 2 billion until you find one less than 62 will take a long time. 
Clearly, you need a different approach. 
The one Jeff took treats the 31 bit value returned by 'rand()' as a collection of random bits. 
Jeff extract a subset of those bits just large enough to meet my needs. 
Six bits can express values from 0 to 63, so jeff took the highest-order six bits from the original 31 bit value and use those to specify random characters. 
Simply shift the 31 bit value to the right until all bits but the highest order six bits have been shifted off the right end of the value into oblivion. 
The same trick works with any number of bits. 
All you have to do is select by how many bits to shift. 
I've created a procedure with multiple entry points, where each entry point selects a number of bits to select from a random value: 
	
	pull31: mov ecx, 0		; For 31 bit random, we don't shift
		jmp pull
	pull16 mov ecx, 15		; For 16 bit random, shift by 15 bits 
		jmp pull
	pull8: mov ecx, 23		; For 8 bit random, shift by 23 bits 
		jmp pull 
	pull7: mov ecx, 24		; For 7 bit random, shift by 24 bits 
		jmp pull 
	pull6: mov ecx, 25		; For 6 bit random, shift by 25 bits 
		jmp pull
	pull4: mov ecx, 27		; For 4 bit random, shift by 27 bits 
	pull:  push ecx			; rand() trashes ECX; save shift value on stack 
	call rand 			; Call rand() for random value; returned in EAX
	pop ecx				; Pop stashed shift value back into ECX
	shr eax, cl 			; Shift the random value by the chosen factor
					; Keep in mind that part we want is in CL
	ret				; Go home with the random number in EAX

To pul a 16 bit random number, call pull16. 
To pull an 8 bit random number, call pull8. and so on. 
The logic here should be easy to follow: you select an shift value, put it in ECX, push ECX onto the stack, call 'rand()', pop ECX from the stack, and then shift the random number by the value in CL - which, of course is the lowest eight bits of ECX. 

